  "final_text": "I'll check the fault registers and stack state in parallel \u2014 fault status from SCB, plus the current MSP/PSP values.\nLet me read the full SCB dump to inspect CFSR (the fault-status bits) and also pull the linker map to know where the stack region sits.\nCFSR is clean \u2014 no fault recorded yet. The target is halted at PC=`0x08013074` (VCATCH, so a reset-hold, not a crash). Let me identify which project is running and then check the stack region against the current SP.\nNow let me identify the active project from the PC address and measure the actual stack headroom (SP vs. `_end`/heap top).\nGood data. Now let me look at the FAULTING project's source \u2014 that PC lives in FAULTING flash \u2014 and check the RAM near `__bss_end__` (the floor of the stack) for corruption.\nLet me look at the FAULTING project's source to understand what kind of fault it's designed to trigger.\nThe picture is complete. Here's what the hardware actually shows:\n\n---\n\n## No stack overflow \u2014 the fault is an undefined instruction\n\n**Stack is clean:**\n| Symbol | Value | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| `_estack` | `0x20018000` | top of 96 KB SRAM1 \u2014 initial SP \u2713 |\n| `__bss_end__` | `0x200000B4` | end of static data (only 180 bytes) |\n| Stack headroom | **~95 KB** | way too much to overflow |\n| Current SP | `0x20018000` | exactly at `_estack` \u2014 pristine, unused |\n\n**CFSR = 0x00000000** \u2014 not a single fault bit is set. `STKERR`, `MSTKERR`, `STKOF` \u2014 all zero.\n\n**What's really happening:**  \nThe target is halted at the reset vector (`DFSR.VCATCH = 1`) before `main()` has run. When you let it go, `main.c` in the FAULTING fixture will execute:\n\n```c\nHAL_Init();\nSystemClock_Config();\n__asm volatile (\"udf #0\");   // \u2190 Permanently Undefined Instruction, B5.6.21\n```\n\n`UDF #0` raises a **UsageFault / UNDEFINSTR**. Because `SHCSR.USGFAULTENA = 0` (fault handler disabled by default), it immediately escalates to a **HardFault** (`HFSR.FORCED = 1`). This is the intentional behaviour of the FAULTING fixture \u2014 it's designed to test `analyze_hardfault`, not to stress the stack.\n\n**No stack bump needed** \u2014 there's nothing to fix here. `_Min_Stack_Size = 0x400` is just the linker-script sanity floor; the usable stack is the full ~95 KB between BSS and the top of SRAM.\n\nIf you want to see the fault registers populated, just `stm32 debug reset --run` and let it reach the `udf` instruction, then halt and re-read `SCB`. You'll see `CFSR.UNDEFINSTR = 1` and `HFSR.FORCED = 1`."
